29
00:01:25.160 --> 00:01:26.490
up at night?

30
00:01:26.490 --> 00:01:27.750
SUNIL GARG: And that's
a great question.

31
00:01:27.750 --> 00:01:30.180
And, honestly, it's
the one I get more

32
00:01:30.180 --> 00:01:32.700
than any other right now.

33
00:01:32.700 --> 00:01:35.730
So here is what I would say
to my developer audience.

34
00:01:35.730 --> 00:01:39.900
The excitement around agents
is completely justified.

35
00:01:39.900 --> 00:01:43.170
Eight-two percent of leaders
are planning to deploy agents

36
00:01:43.170 --> 00:01:46.140
in the next 12 to 18
months just to keep

37
00:01:46.140 --> 00:01:48.960
up with the workforce demand.

38
00:01:48.960 --> 00:01:52.950
But that same momentum is
what's creating the anxiety

39
00:01:52.950 --> 00:01:55.260
on the other side of the table.

40
00:01:55.260 --> 00:01:57.360
When I talk to CISOs and CIOs,

41
00:01:57.360 --> 00:02:00.120
four things
consistently come up.

42
00:02:00.120 --> 00:02:04.290
First, agent sprawl
and resource access.

43
00:02:04.290 --> 00:02:08.820
Every team is spinning up agents
and each one needs identity,

44
00:02:08.820 --> 00:02:12.420
permissions, and access
to data and tools.

45
00:02:12.420 --> 00:02:15.690
The most important shift
in your mental model

46
00:02:15.690 --> 00:02:20.880
as a developer is this,
an agent is not an app,

47
00:02:20.880 --> 00:02:24.180
it's an actor with
its own brain.

48
00:02:24.180 --> 00:02:28.260
Give it a scoped identity,
least privilege access,

49
00:02:28.260 --> 00:02:31.290
and an audit trail from day one.

50
00:02:31.290 --> 00:02:36.030
If you bolt on governance later,
you have already lost it.

51
00:02:36.030 --> 00:02:39.560
Second, data oversharing.

52
00:02:39.560 --> 00:02:43.580
Eighty percent of leaders
tell us their top concern is

53
00:02:43.580 --> 00:02:47.390
sensitive data
leaking through AI.

54
00:02:47.390 --> 00:02:50.460
This usually isn't
a model problem,

55
00:02:50.460 --> 00:02:52.770
it's a grounding problem.

56
00:02:52.770 --> 00:02:57.450
The agent has access to, say,
a SharePoint site, a CRM,

57
00:02:57.450 --> 00:03:01.950
an email thread that the
user technically can reach,

58
00:03:01.950 --> 00:03:05.580
but probably shouldn't be
surfacing in this context.

59
00:03:05.580 --> 00:03:10.980
Developers need to design agents
with data boundaries in mind,

60
00:03:10.980 --> 00:03:14.940
agents respecting sensitivity
labels, honoring the permissions

61
00:03:14.940 --> 00:03:17.520
of the user invoking the agent,

62
00:03:17.520 --> 00:03:21.930
and never let the agent become
a shortcut around controls

63
00:03:21.930 --> 00:03:25.950
that already exist
in the enterprise.

64
00:03:25.950 --> 00:03:29.190
Third, the new threat surface.

65
00:03:29.190 --> 00:03:32.010
Eighty-eight percent of
organizations are worried

66
00:03:32.010 --> 00:03:37.140
about indirect prompt
injections, and they should be.

67
00:03:37.140 --> 00:03:41.010
The moment your agent reads
an email, parses a document,

68
00:03:41.010 --> 00:03:45.750
or browses a web page,
untrusted content enters its

69
00:03:45.750 --> 00:03:47.250
reasoning loop.

70
00:03:47.250 --> 00:03:51.390
As developers, our job is
to build the right hooks

71
00:03:51.390 --> 00:03:53.850
and guardrails into our agents

72
00:03:53.850 --> 00:03:57.600
so enterprise security teams
can detect and respond

73
00:03:57.600 --> 00:04:00.240
to these attempted threats.

74
00:04:00.240 --> 00:04:03.360
That's where tools
like Defender plug in.

75
00:04:03.360 --> 00:04:07.080
Assume your agent will be
manipulated and designed

76
00:04:07.080 --> 00:04:10.020
for graceful failure when it is.

77
00:04:10.020 --> 00:04:13.830
And, fourth, regulatory
uncertainty.

78
00:04:13.830 --> 00:04:16.470
More than half of
the leaders I talk

79
00:04:16.470 --> 00:04:22.080
to admit don't fully understand
how AI will be regulated,

80
00:04:22.080 --> 00:04:25.500
the EU sector specific
rules in finance

81
00:04:25.500 --> 00:04:30.720
and healthcare evolving
guidance in the U.S. My advice,

82
00:04:30.720 --> 00:04:33.450
don't wait for the
rules to settle,

83
00:04:33.450 --> 00:04:37.970
build observability
and traceability now.

84
00:04:37.970 --> 00:04:43.820
If you can answer what did
this agent do on whose behalf

85
00:04:43.820 --> 00:04:46.790
with what data and
why, you are ready

86
00:04:46.790 --> 00:04:49.190
for whatever framework lands.

87
00:04:49.190 --> 00:04:52.290
So what's keeping enterprise
customers up at night?

88
00:04:52.290 --> 00:04:54.420
Well, it's not one of these.

89
00:04:54.420 --> 00:04:56.910
It's the compounding risk.

90
00:04:56.910 --> 00:05:02.010
An agent with too much access,
reasoning over untrusted data,

91
00:05:02.010 --> 00:05:04.860
making decisions
no one can audit

92
00:05:04.860 --> 00:05:09.510
in a regulatory environment
that's still being written,

93
00:05:09.510 --> 00:05:10.950
that is the risk.

94
00:05:10.950 --> 00:05:15.570
The good news is every one of
these problems has an answer.

95
00:05:15.570 --> 00:05:19.890
And most of those answers are
things developers control,

96
00:05:19.890 --> 00:05:23.460
which is exactly what I would
love to dig into today.

97
00:05:23.460 --> 00:05:28.230
Look, the developers who win
here aren't the ones shipping

98
00:05:28.230 --> 00:05:32.820
the flashiest agents, they
are the ones building agents

99
00:05:32.820 --> 00:05:35.610
that CISOs will
actually approve.

100
00:05:35.610 --> 00:05:36.000
JEREMIAH FOLLIS: Wow.

101
00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.650
So that agent as an actor
framing is a big mindset shift.

102
00:05:40.650 --> 00:05:42.150
Walk us through it.

103
00:05:42.150 --> 00:05:44.160
When an enterprise
is bringing an agent

104
00:05:44.160 --> 00:05:45.840
into their organization,

105
00:05:45.840 --> 00:05:48.510
what are the questions
that they're asking?

106
00:05:48.510 --> 00:05:51.060
SUNIL GARG: Yeah, let
me build on that agent

107
00:05:51.060 --> 00:05:54.360
as an actor idea because
it's the frame shift

108
00:05:54.360 --> 00:05:56.940
that unlocks everything else.

109
00:05:56.940 --> 00:05:59.460
So we need to stop
thinking about agents

110
00:05:59.460 --> 00:06:03.210
as features inside an
application, and start thinking

111
00:06:03.210 --> 00:06:06.690
of them as members
of the workforce.

112
00:06:06.690 --> 00:06:09.030
When a new employee
joins your company,

113
00:06:09.030 --> 00:06:11.370
an entire machinery kicks in.

114
00:06:11.370 --> 00:06:14.760
IT provisions a managed
identity, their access is scoped

115
00:06:14.760 --> 00:06:18.060
to their role, their
manager sets expectations,

116
00:06:18.060 --> 00:06:20.940
and everything they
do is auditable.

117
00:06:20.940 --> 00:06:23.460
Nobody calls that
bureaucratic overhead.

118
00:06:23.460 --> 00:06:27.180
That's just how organizations
operate at scale.

119
00:06:27.180 --> 00:06:30.180
Agents need the same treatment.

120
00:06:30.180 --> 00:06:34.020
And the questions enterprise
customers ask maps almost

121
00:06:34.020 --> 00:06:36.540
one-on-one to these
questions they would ask

122
00:06:36.540 --> 00:06:38.910
about any new hire.

123
00:06:38.910 --> 00:06:41.670
Can IT discover and manage them?

124
00:06:41.670 --> 00:06:44.040
Today, mostly no.

125
00:06:44.040 --> 00:06:47.820
Register your agents with an
identity from day one because,

126
00:06:47.820 --> 00:06:52.380
if IT can't see it,
IT can't protect it.

127
00:06:52.380 --> 00:06:56.700
Second, who are they sharing
sensitive information with?

128
00:06:56.700 --> 00:06:59.460
Think about flows of data,
not just permissions

129
00:06:59.460 --> 00:07:01.410
on individual actions.

130
00:07:01.410 --> 00:07:05.070
An agent can have two perfectly
reasonable permissions

131
00:07:05.070 --> 00:07:09.450
on their own, read from
a CRM, send an email,

132
00:07:09.450 --> 00:07:13.230
and the combination still
creates an exfiltration path

133
00:07:13.230 --> 00:07:15.300
designed with the
full flow in mind,

134
00:07:15.300 --> 00:07:18.720
not just the individual action.

135
00:07:18.720 --> 00:07:20.880
Are they behaving properly?

136
00:07:20.880 --> 00:07:23.910
Build in the telemetry,
behavioral signals,

137
00:07:23.910 --> 00:07:27.960
and hooks that let enterprise
security teams monitor

138
00:07:27.960 --> 00:07:29.790
and course correct.

139
00:07:29.790 --> 00:07:33.780
You can't fix what
you can't see.

140
00:07:33.780 --> 00:07:35.970
Are they well
governed and audited?

141
00:07:35.970 --> 00:07:38.880
Every action needs
to be attributable,

142
00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:45.330
which agent on whose behalf
with what data to what outcome.

143
00:07:45.330 --> 00:07:48.210
So my guidance for developers,

144
00:07:48.210 --> 00:07:53.340
the bar for an enterprise-ready
agent isn't whether it works,

145
00:07:53.340 --> 00:07:56.610
it's whether it could
pass an onboarding review

146
00:07:56.610 --> 00:07:58.770
at a Fortune 500.

147
00:07:58.770 --> 00:08:02.850
Identity, behavior, data
handling, auditability,

148
00:08:02.850 --> 00:08:07.410
build to that bar and you are
not just building agents people

149
00:08:07.410 --> 00:08:12.180
will use, you are building
agents enterprise will trust.

150
00:08:12.180 --> 00:08:16.570
And trust is what takes
a demo to production.

151
00:08:18.600 --> 00:08:20.160
JEREMIAH FOLLIS: So
that bar, I mean,

152
00:08:20.160 --> 00:08:24.720
passing a Fortune 500
onboarding review is high.

153
00:08:24.720 --> 00:08:29.010
And, honestly, for a developer
just trying to ship an agent,

154
00:08:29.010 --> 00:08:31.170
all of this can
feel overwhelming.

155
00:08:31.170 --> 00:08:35.160
What's your guidance of how does
Microsoft help developers clear

156
00:08:35.160 --> 00:08:39.720
that bar without rebuilding
the security stack themselves?

157
00:08:39.720 --> 00:08:42.630
SUNIL GARG: Yes, you
are spot on, Jeremiah.

158
00:08:42.630 --> 00:08:45.510
It has been a big pain
point for developers

159
00:08:45.510 --> 00:08:49.830
to build enterprise-ready
agents because they may need

160
00:08:49.830 --> 00:08:53.570
to use a variety of open-source
and development tools.

161
00:08:53.570 --> 00:08:56.330
Sometimes they need
to justify, identify,

162
00:08:56.330 --> 00:08:58.940
and patch these
controls themselves,

163
00:08:58.940 --> 00:09:02.510
let alone figuring it out how
customers will eventually use

164
00:09:02.510 --> 00:09:06.290
and benefit from these
bespoke implementations.

165
00:09:06.290 --> 00:09:09.800
So the bottom line is
that it's challenging

166
00:09:09.800 --> 00:09:13.700
to maintain various controls
from different vendors

167
00:09:13.700 --> 00:09:15.720
and make them all
enterprise proofed.

168
00:09:15.720 --> 00:09:19.620
At Microsoft, we really want
to help solve this challenge

169
00:09:19.620 --> 00:09:21.990
for developers to
enable security

170
00:09:21.990 --> 00:09:26.160
and governance controls easily
in the agents they build,

171
00:09:26.160 --> 00:09:29.250
no matter where they build
it, how they build it,

172
00:09:29.250 --> 00:09:31.230
and where they run it.

173
00:09:31.230 --> 00:09:33.630
That's where Agent 365 comes in.

174
00:09:33.630 --> 00:09:37.290
Agent 365 is the control
plane for agents,

175
00:09:37.290 --> 00:09:41.280
built so enterprise customers
can observe, govern,

176
00:09:41.280 --> 00:09:45.300
and secure every agent
in their environment.

177
00:09:45.300 --> 00:09:49.350
We made Agent 365 generally
available on May 1st along

178
00:09:49.350 --> 00:09:54.180
with the SDK, and the SDK is
what makes everything real

179
00:09:54.180 --> 00:09:55.980
for developers.

180
00:09:55.980 --> 00:10:01.350
So, for the rest of the session,
I will focus exactly on that,

181
00:10:01.350 --> 00:10:04.620
how you as a developer
can use the SDK

182
00:10:04.620 --> 00:10:08.400
to make your agent fully
observable, manageable,

183
00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:12.220
and governable by Agent 365.

184
00:10:13.320 --> 00:10:14.880
JEREMIAH FOLLIS: So
building on that,

185
00:10:14.880 --> 00:10:19.860
Agent 365 also gives
developers a clear path

186
00:10:19.860 --> 00:10:24.740
to make sure the agents they
build are manageable inside it.

187
00:10:24.740 --> 00:10:29.700
Sunil, when a maker or
a developer is working

188
00:10:29.700 --> 00:10:33.180
in Agent Builder, Copilot
Studio, or Foundry,

189
00:10:33.180 --> 00:10:34.830
what do they need to do

